value.0:
The Wave & Serpent Adventuring Guild is where most adventurers congregate when they first arrive on Amia. Here, you will find a multitude of shops and personalities, as well as information about the island and direct access to a mythal forge.

The Guild is led by a group of seasoned Guildmasters who often give out quests or jobs of varying levels of difficulty. Come by often to keep up to date on the latest offerings!

This statue will take you to a variety of different portals for faction or settlement start locations on Amia. They require specific keys or items to use, so there is no need to enter this statue if you are not part of a faction or settlement with a key and unique starting location.

Amia is not alone out there where the Sea of Swords meets the Trackless Sea. Those who go to the island seeking adventure can find other opportunities within a few days of sea travel. Nearest to Amia is the grim island of Ruathym and its fractious jarldoms: Wiltun, which claims one of the most powerful navies in the Sea of Swords and which regularly wars with Luskan trade ships; Caraigh, a mineral rich area of Ruathym beset by the sins of its past; and Ostland, the only truly fertile landscape in Ruathym. There is also Forrstakkr, a backwater island that features some of the most beautiful and regular aurora borealis in the world, as well as Barak Runedar, home to dwarves who were so long ago run from their ancient undermountain home, but have long sought to reclaim what is rightfully theirs.

Explorers can also find adventure on the northern coast of the mainland in the Frozenfar region, making port in Endir's Point and exploring the surrounding hinterlands and other points of interest like the ironically named Fort Summer and the lost dwarven citadel of Barak Tungstuk. Particularly canny adventurers abandon the surface altogether and travel underground to explore the dangerous depths of the Underdark, where the denizens have built civilizations like the slave colony of L'Obsul and the mysterious Nec'perya, a drow enclave nestled in the middle of dangerous faezress.

Forrstakkr is not a major tourist attraction. Nor is it a major trade destination. The hard-working and disciplined people of Forrstakkr's only major port of Howness, however, have made the icy island a reliable manufacturer of goods. Pelts hunted from local wildlife make excellent leather and hide for local tailors, while the tall pines of the Niflwood provide carpenters with adequate lumber for furnishings. An ancient glacier tore mineral from the earth ages ago and now the natives mine iron and make good and sturdy steel parts from it.

The major draw in Forrstakkr is for hunters, adventurers, and man against nature survivalists. The wilderness on the island is both dangerous and beautiful, featuring untamed wildlife such as winter wolves who hunt in packs among snow-draped conifers and snow leopards hiding in the glacial ridges colored by the unique lights that manifest in the sky. Howness locals are very isolationist and keep strangers at arm's length. The mistrust comes from a combination of merchant shysters trying to take advantage of them in the past as well as devout Aurilities that bring winter's wrath to their wooden barricades all too often.

The people in the small village of Ceyren's Mill live private and detached lives isolated from the once-tained countryside and suspicious of strangers who come from the wilderness, but their rustic living has a certain charm to it for people seeking a simple life of simple tasks. Travelers can reach the island of Caraigh by ship, and Ceyren's Mill is a short and relatively safe walk due north. Geographically, Caraigh is located east of Ruathym, a larger island weighed down by a history of tragedy, with some semblance of peace finally settling when the Jarldom of Wiltun staked a claim on the land. 

Deeper in the badlands of the island lie ruins in old druidic fashion, said to be the remains of the followers of Eldath. Their disappearance remains a mystery, as do many things on the island. Other destinations are not so mysterious, but are certainly unique, such as a lighthouse/observatory and a sanatorium on the northern bluffs of the island.

Citizens of Ceyren's Mill will tell the tales of their homeland, but most of them do not venture out to create new ones.

The island of Amia lies at the farthest edge of the Sea of Swords, directly along what Sword Coast merchants call the Trackless Trade Route that carries merchants and their goods to and from foreign ports like Kara-Tur, Maztica, and Chult. Amia and its small port city of Southport is a primary stopping point for trade ships moving through the open ocean, but where merchants enjoy the island for its money exchange, trade opportunities, luxury markets and sometimes a nice seaside vacation, many others are drawn to the island for its promise of adventure.

It may have been a canny move on behalf of a tourism expert, but Amia developed a reputation as an adventurer's paradise generations ago and is still characterized that way to this day on mainland Faerun. Adventurers that come to Amia almost always arrive by large passenger vessel in the port city of Southport and find themselves just north in Frontier's Rest, where they heed the call of the Wave and Serpent Adventuring Guild. From there they can travel by ship or by cart to most civilized points of the island, and by foot to the island's wilder frontier.

Other unique communities exist on Amia for those seeking something the major settlements lack. The Crouching Lemur monastery in the foothills of the Skull Crags offers a monastic living for those who eschew the excesses of the major trade-influenced cities. Likewise, for those dedicated wholly to the balance of nature, the Oakmist Vale druid's grove north of the halfling home known as The Dale makes an excellent haven.

Further up the coast along the waters of Silent Bay are temple grounds dedicated to Salandra, a regional goddess of healing. The Salandran Temple is visited by wealthy nobles and personalities from as far away as mainland Faerun, and the temple grounds have gotten the reputation as a livewell resort for individuals with ailments physical, mental, and spiritual that traditional magic cannot cure. Sellswords and other mercenaries are welcome in the Mercenary's Camp nestled within the Quagmire swamps. West from there, the small Duchy of Fort Cystana lies on an outcropping which some say mysteriously fell from the sky and landed on the northern coast.

The Republic of Southport is a nation made up of Southport, Traveller's Rest, and Ridgewood. It is a Waukeenar republic founded on trade and prosperity.

Each district within Southport, as well as Traveller's Rest and Ridgewood, has representative Ministers who speak on behalf of their citizens during governmental meetings. Each district or settlement has their own laws and governance.

Southport has known a few names over the generations: the Gem of the Trackless Sea, the City of Tolerance, the City of Water, and the Commonwealth, when the citizens, aggrieved with the noble caste, politically dismantled the establishment and instituted a citizens' government. In spite of the city's instability, one core factor has ever remained consistent: the port city has always been a hotspot that draws trade both foreign and domestic to its streets and market halls, so much so that the city once housed one of the largest Waukeenar churches in Toril. A great calamity now sees most of the former Jewel of the Trackless Sea sunk to the bottom of the ocean.

In an effort to curb their resultant vulnerability, they formed an alliance with Traveller's Rest and Ridgewood and came together as the Kingdom of Cetha, but even this fell to chaos due to the assassination of King Adam Fairchild. After much unrest, they instead formed a Waukeenar Republic of Southport, built on commerce and trade. Traveller's Rest and Ridgewood returned to their former alliance, joining the Republic.

Southport prides itself as a city of commerce and, indeed, many merchant guilds have cropped up in recent years. But one thing is certain; where there is coin, there is always another side to said coin.

Traveller's Rest is located just north of Southport and is home to the Wave & Serpent Adventuring Guild. A small "suburb" town, Traveller's Rest is largely self-sufficient and carefully protected by the Guildhouse. They are, however, close with their neighbors. Much of Southport's food comes from Traveller's Rest. It is also part of the Waukeenar Republic of Southport, which is made up of Southport, Traveller's Rest, and Ridgewood.

Visitors to the island tend to reach Southport by sea travel and dock at the ports in its western district, where they can find cheap housing and access to nearby shops. Merchants and tourists are the city's primary visitors, each drawn distinctly by the things the island of Amia has to offer them, with Southport often being their first taste of the island. The rough and rowdy locals often make guests gravitate to the more peaceful and friendly Traveller's Rest in due time, however.

Adventurers are drawn to the island in abundance as well by the promise of wealth, glory, and adventure. While Traveller's Rest and Southport are surrounded by hazards - coastal marshes of dangerous animals and bandits to the west, warrior tribes of goblins and orcs to the north, and stranger creatures along the shorelines to the east - it is highly defensible. For some reason, they say extremely large reptiles are something of an exception to this rule.

A part of the Republic of Southport, Ridgewood is a small logging settlement located within the Skull Peaks, a chain of mountains on the eastern edge of the isle of Amia. It is most known for its log and plank exports, sustainable long-term due to their constant reforestation efforts and selective logging. Other exports to come out of Ridgewood include stone and gem ore, which they mine from the mountain.

The people of Ridgewood are stout and accustomed to hard work. They have lived mostly self-sustainably on produce they grow outside their homes, but they do import meat and other goods they can't grow despite their strangely warm environment, which some rumor to be the result of a magical artifact that keeps the weather crisp and pleasant like the middle of Spring.
Put items that you not longer want or need in the trash. They will vanish permanently once the lid is closed and cannot be recovered, so be certain about your choice to dispose of them.

The Kingdom of Kohlingen is a nation located on the northern end of the isle of Amia. Made up of Fort Cystana, Greengarden, and Gregory's Landing, it is a large kingdom of holy warriors and devout followers of The Triad, Bahamut, and a variety of goodly deities. Paladins, clerics of goodly deities, and those who have the blood of metallic dragons and celestials call Kohlingen home alongside the thousands of citizens under the Kingdom's protection.

Led by a Regent chosen by the people until a time when the Crown Prince comes of age and can assume the throne, the Kingdom of Kohlingen is a noble, goodly place with a strong military and naval presence.
These lovely flowers are in bloom and give off a sweet scent.

Fort Cystana is a Duchy in the Kingdom of Kohlingen. It is located on the northwest coast of Amia. The people of the Fort Cystana mostly hailed from the great Holy City of Kohlingen, which was located on the northeastern coast of the isle. The land there was once tainted by great evil, but was purified and has since become the Duchy of Greengarden.

Fort Cystana is the capital of the Kingdom of Kohlingen, housing the Argent Keep, the seat of the Regent and much of the kingdom's military. The vast majority of the Navy also works out of Fort Cystana.

Gregory's Landing is a Duchy of the Kingdom of Kohlingen, named to Honor the late King Gregory Simmons, who gave his life to cleanse the once-tainted land. The area is now known for its beautiful, lush meadows where the horses of the Kingdom's Cavalry graze.

It is marked by a fusion between the charm of small-town life and the bustle of a military town. Where one might believe these lifestyles would normally collide, they blend here in unique harmony. A rustic tavern rests opposite the stables, where guards and civilians meet to enjoy an ale and a hot meal alongside jolly music. Surrounded by small shops and backed by the soldier barracks and training facilities, you can find a bit of everything in this place.

Nestled on the edge of Benwick Bay on the northeast coast of the island, Kampo's Storehouse has been the meeting point of outlaws, smugglers, and lawless travelers with pasts too circumspect for them to reside in nearby Kohlingen or even distant Cordor. That isn't to say the Storehouse caters exclusively to the island's most nefarious characters, but rather it caters to anyone with coin and a drive to earn more of it. Kampo has made an arrangement with Amian Cart Services to guarantee that they will stop by to supply and give passage to anyone willing to pay for it.

Kampo is a devout follower of Waukeen and an advocate of tolerance. Not much is known about the half-orc's past but the man accumulated enough wealth to establish his trade house on the main thoroughfare of trade along the bay. Recently, the nearby Eilistraeen Shrine funded the refurbishment of the Storehouse with the assistance of adventurers following a bar brawl that devastated the structure. Golems now defend the Storehouse alongside Kampo's own hired guards, acting as a deterrent to anyone foolish enough to "pull that crap again".

Anyone looking for information, goods or mercenaries can find them at the Storehouse. If not, Kampo will know where to look.

An honored place of healing and care for all those under the good graces of the gods to find much-needed respite from the many woes that inflict the good citizens of Amia. Salandra welcomes all those talented in the healing arts to seek out her temple and join in bringing relief to the sick and needy who come in search of cures and healing.

Salandra the Healer is a demigod under Ilmaters service. Once a mortal priestess of the Crying God on the island of Amia, she dedicated her life to the treatment of illness and eradication of undeath. Eventually, she faced a martyrs fate when stopping a devastating malady, and Ilmater saw fit to reward her devotion with divinity.

Salandras temples are few and far between. The oldest one is located here on Amia, her home island. There are a handful of other small temples on Toril: on the Moonshaes, somewhere in the Dalelands, and in Tethyr. Small shrines exist in a few Ilmateri temples.

The primary duty of Salandrans is to treat wounds and cure illnesses, offering a helping hand to anyone in need. The clergy members are renowned for their skill with herbs, surgery, and other forms of treatment for ailments of both body and spirit. Every servant is expected to learn the basics of medicine. Mundane forms of healing are preferred to those of divine nature whenever possible.

The beautiful elven enclave of Winya Ravana, located in the verdant Nexus Hills and upstream to the Nexus Falls, is a uniquely elven blend of civilized structure sharing the same space as natural features. The City of the People is a sapphire and emerald paradise, strewn with lush copses of oak and aspen, cool clear streams, and everywhere the sacred magic of the elves. Winya Ravana, which in elven means "new forests", is most easily reached by taking a cart to the Nexus Hills and then ascending the bluffs that form the breathtaking Nexus Falls, where the currents from the citys many pure springs coarse down into a valley to form the Minmir River. Through the mist and spray atop the Falls, one may witness the most magnificent sunsets on Amia.

Winya Ravana itself consists of two areas: the Outer Sanctum and the Inner Sanctum. These two sancta are connected by bridge over a crystalline lake which feeds the Nexus. The Outer Sanctum is open to kin and friends of the People alike and offers much to see and do: situated in the center of this sanctum looms an enormous and ancient tree that covers the Market Square. Here you may also find a talented elven smith as well as the Iron Butterfly Inn, famed for its elven cuisine and a lush apple orchard. The Outer Sanctum is also a superb area for fishing.

To the north across the bridge lies the Inner Sanctum, the spiritual center of Winya Ravana. This sacred field is open only to the sons and daughters of The Seldarine. Guests of the People, however, are welcome in company of kin. Shrines to each member of the Seldarine can be found both inside and outside the grand Temple of Corellon. There are also a few tree houses here where a keen eye may spy a sly-but-friendly fey creature. The Inner Sanctum also holds an archery range and a bathhouse and lounge area between the spiritual centers of the Temple.

"All roads lead to The Dale" is a popular saying amongst Amian traders. Due to its prime central location on the island, The Dale is a waypoint and rest stop for caravans and travelers using the trade roads across the Amian island. The village is populated almost exclusively by hin, though other fairfolk races such as gnomes, dwarves, and smaller fey are welcomed as citizens. Agriculture plays a key part in the Dale. The apple orchard in particular is well known. Wayfarers often visit the Hin Inn, a taller-friendly establishment that boasts some of Amia's best food and drinks from around the island, as well as a tradition of folk music. The Inn is more than a place for drink and merriment, though; with people traveling through The Dale from all points on the island and with the locals' penchant for storytelling, the gossip is great. Before they leave visitors are encouraged to resupply with the village's many homegrown goods, from arcane goods to healing supplies and traveling goods.

The Dale's centrality has a downside, though. Orcs to the south, trolls to the east, and mylocks on the west pose constant threats to the otherwise peaceful village, necessitating a strong hin militia and vigilant border camps. The Amia Forest spreads to the north and is otherwise peaceful thanks to the Oakmist Vale druid grove nestled deep in the trees. Unless you stray from the path and encounter the wild creatures that roam near there.

Boredom is the only thing unwelcome in The Dale, so playful tricks and pranks for a good laugh at someone's expense aren't uncommon. Beware to those of ill humor.
(Description coming soon! This is a settlement for monster races! Goblins, Hobgoblins, Kobolds, Orcs, Orogs, Ogrillons, etc.)

Blue Lagoon is a small port settlement on the northern tip of the island of Amia. It is home to sailors, pirates, and buccaneers alike, a town of trade and the spread of information, it has a busy port despite its size. Once a part of Chalkcliff Island, it has gradually become a new hotspot of activity for a variety of people.

Nearest to Amia of all the Ruathym Jarldoms, The Jarldom of Wiltun is comprised of Fortress Wiltun and the island of Caraigh. The Ironguard of Wiltun, an oathbound group of warriors and guards sworn to protect the realm under its rightful chieftain, retain the martial hand of the Wiltun jarldom, whether in Fortress Wiltun or in the town of Ceyren's Mill on Caraigh.

Ruathym's mariners often work gladly in Wiltun's navy, which features one of the largest armadas in the northern seas, rivaled only by the Kohlinger navy. The Wiltun navy escorts several wealthy trade ships past the Ruathym coast, as well as Ruathym's sworn enemy, the nefarious Luskans, whom through piracy and arcane trickery have instilled in some of the people of Ruathym a great mistrust for magic. Spellcasters are still welcome in the jarldoms of Wiltun and Ostand, but a number of Ruathymi citizens still look upon them initially with a keen wariness.

Ruathym's largest jarldom is Ostland, located near the eastern coast of Ruathym. Having spent the greater amount of time in constant warfare, the total region of Ostland was until recent prospecting starved of natural resources used to fuel the conflict. Veins of ore and precious metals have since been located, and a number of kobolds, bound to serve the Jarl in some manner, have aided in excavation and mining.

Without brave men and women to fight its war, Ostland's conflicts bear no expectations of a peaceful solution, so mercenaries may find plenty of work in the jarldom. Like other places in Ruathym, magic had been scorned and hated for many years in Ostland, but recent times have turned bitterness to cautious acceptance as countless magical spellcasters of all walks of life have offered only aid to them.

Rumors tell of a terrifying lich who lairs deep beneath the swampy region known as The Slough.

The Triumvir is a demiplane interconnected by a network of lamp portals to many different places on the island of Amia and abroad. The Triumvir is a home for bards and storytellers, where the joy of song and narrative holds fast. The demiplane is known to be openly neutral to all powers to which it is connected, but the safety of its residents is paramount and troublemakers are not welcome.

Theatrical performances, dances, festivals, and concerts are just a small number of the different events one can expect to encounter at the Triumvir.

In the harsh environment of the Shadow Plane, there is an oasis of civilization called Shadowscape. The city is magically protected, shielding visitors and citizens alike from the worst effects of living on the plane. Amians can reach Shadowscape through a planar rift located in the Trummels of the Amia Forest, but only after traveling through some dangerous wilderness. Smaller rifts are rumored to be somewhere in Brogendenstein and Endirs Point in the Frozenfar, however these lead to more dangerous areas of the plane that are outside the safety of the citys walls. The Keeper of Shadows hosts a city with everything you might need. In the market square there are merchants carrying wares of magical shadesteel, including a special outlet that caters to dedicated Shadow Walkers, and somewhere in the city is a discreet temple to Mask.

The city is home to the notorious Three Steps Academy. The Academy, as it is more commonly called, offers elite training in the art of shadowdancing. Dancers of any proficiency level, from beginners to masters, are welcome and have the opportunity to also learn about shadow plane theory and science, shade mastery, and more advanced forms of the art. For visitors wanting to take in the everpresent night life of Shadowscape, the Drunk Dancer Inn promises luxurious lodging, exquisite brews and refreshment, and decadent entertainment. This glittering jewel is conveniently located in the northwest corner on the citys second tier and commands an impressive view over the her dark beauty.

Endir's Point is the end of the line for many mainland travelers scouring the Sword Coast, some from as far away as Calimsham. Located on the icy tip of the Frozenfar's coast, Endir's Point is reached by sailing vessel by most and on foot only by the bravest or most foolish, such as founder Endir himself, for whom conflicting stories of courage and idiocy abound. Like many communities near to the Spine of the World and the great glacier, mining is an important local industry in Endir's Point. The presence of a rift to the Shadow Plane has started trade between Endir's Point and the shadow plane city of Shadowscape, affording the small village more amenities than most villages in the Frozenfar. Travelers almost always visit the shrine to Shaundakul to venerate the god of the roads and then to have some warm mead or Ralten's Special at the local inn and tavern, Ralten's Retreat.

Adventurers who travel into the hinterlands around Endir's Point should be wary of the bloodthirsty trolls, orcs, ogres, and wintery fey that dominate the wild. But in spite of the danger they present, there are many things to be found in the abandoned Fort Summer to the east, the frozen lake and the ruins of Barak Tungstak to the north, and a grand Ice Palace of Auril to the west.

Nes'ek is mostly a Lathanderan settlement in the center of the Ankh'remun Desert in Khem. The Church of Hoar and of Kelemvor now both also reside in it. The church of Lathander is on strained terms with the clergy of the Mulhorandi pantheon. This conflict originates through the race for more followers and the claims of both sides to be the true faith of Khem. The Church of Hoar often even stands in direct confrontation with the faithful of the Eight, most notably the faith of Anhur.

The township is also often caught up in the struggles between the Bedine and Minotaurs. The clergy of Lathander often tasks adventurers with the job of putting down the Sand Minotaurs. Nes'ek is reached via a portal on the top of the keep in Fortress Wiltun, or through the portal lens of the travel lamps around Amia and joining areas of the mainland.

L'Obsul is a confusing mess of a settlement like many found throughout the uncharted Underdark. While difficult for many to pronounce (and it would be wisest not to try), L'Obsul stands for "door" in the tongue of the drow and the drow are the true leaders of this unruly place. House Zau'tar, a noble and prideful group of drow, control the political and economic institutions of L'Obsul yet are not above dealing with others races that are willing to work quietly under the table. Almost anyone is allowed into their complex, but not everyone comes out; those who stay in L'Obsul learn to be wary of its delicate caste system. Anyone can end up in chains.

Many tunnels lead away from L'Obsul in different directions, and very few of them are safe, providing fertile hunting grounds for adventurers of varied experience, everything from rats to the basest of kobolds, as well as mindflayers and beholders for those seeking greater glory in The Deeper Dark.


((WARNING: If your character is not an Underdark character, take extreme care in journeying here. The Underdark is no place for sacrificial Surfacer fodder.))

A tropical island located to the southwest of Amia, Obsidian Isle is a lavish paradise which holds a more nefarious undertone alongside a checkered history layered with good and evil.

Calderis is a stronghold city built along the southeastern coast of Obsidian Isle. Home to wicked followers of gods like Velsharoon and Jergal, it is not unheard of to encounter undead about the city. Calderis is headed by a council of representatives who handle all manner of day-to-day business.
These lovely flowers are in bloom and give off a sweet scent.

The Mercenary Camp, located in the Quagmire Swamp near the northern end of the island of Amia, is home to a friendly tribe of Lizardfolk: the Red Tribe. They have become a band of mercenaries that largely keep to themselves except to fight against the Green Tribe of lizardfolk that live in the swamps themselves. They have had dealings with many of the other settlements on Amia.

A tribe of kobolds lives in this area, underground beneath the mercenary camp. These kobolds are largely neutral and do not act with the violence usually known to their kind. They also prefer to keep to themselves and stay out of trouble.

The Shrine of Eilistraee is small settlement built into the hillside, housing a small Eilistraeen drow population. Other monstrous creatures who have sought atonement from their more murderous ways also call the place home, although they are mostly unseen.

The Shrine of Eilistraee has a long, checkered past, but they stand as a testament to their Maiden's cause: to aid those who seek a peaceful home away from the darkness. The dedicated drow of the Shrine do all they can both to aid their neighbors and to help their kin from Below to walk in the light.

Moonpier is on the western coast of Amia, separated from Southport territory by the Delta freelands and the bandits who dominate the highway connecting the fishing village and the large port city. Though it was originally established over a century ago as an outpost and secondary port to supplement trade and growth, the powers-that-were never saw fit to truly exercise any authority in the village. Moonpier's inhabitants support themselves on the fishing trade and local agriculture.

Throughout the years, they were often forced to fight their own battles against pirates, bandits, and orcish raiders who descended upon them from the inland hills. Eventually they elected their own mayor both out of a necessity for local government and as a statement of autonomy. Only once did Southport's predecessor attempt to assert its authority over Moonpier, but the political annexation was weak in execution and merely bolstered the reality that Moonpier is truly an independent community.

The village has very little to offer to tourists, but adventurers who travel through Amia find a more welcoming atmosphere in Moonpier than in other settlements, despite the town's obvious troubles. The local militia is a strong and dedicated one, but ultimately friendly to adventurers provided they observe the town's peaceful ways. Some suggest this has something to do with the militia being populated by a few former adventure-seekers. The worship of Selune is the predominant faith in Moonpier, and the village was once known to support an open-air temple to the goddess of the moon. The citizens have long been dedicated to the religion, save for a troubled year of Banite occupation. A new church took the place of the destroyed temple, which features an invisible ceiling that always lets in the light of the moon when night falls.

Moonpier is easily and safely reached by sail, cart services, or the portal system from the Triumvir, but intrepid travelers may take their chances traveling north from the Delta on foot.

Oakmist Vale is a druid's grove located in the heart of Amia Forest. The small settlement is also home to numerous rangers who help to keep the area safe, along with a multitude of magical beasts, like unicorns and griffons. Dedicated to preserving the Balance, the people of Oakmist Vale watch over Amia Forest and ensure that anyone who intentionally seeks to harm the forest meets a swift response.

Led by a circle of Archdruids and their Great Druid, Oakmist Vale has had many dealings with nearby allies, with their efforts to thwart Malarite lycans being among the best-known of their deeds.

The Crouching Lemur Monastery is located about midway up the Skull Peaks, along the road between The Dale and Ridgewood. It is home to a number of monks and other protectors who live peacefully with the land. While they have been known to make a stand against certain threats to the innocent people of the island, they are a largely neutral people who are content to live in harmony with all things.
This bottle of red wine is of a special vintage and would most assuredly tantalize the palate.
This bottle of red wine is of a special vintage and would most assuredly tantalize the palate.
The many leaves of this bush are so dense that it is almost impossible to see through the foliage.
This rug is beautifully woven, with intricate patterns that draw you in more the closer you look.
This pestilent fungi grows in even the darkest of caves.
These lovely flowers are in bloom and give off a sweet scent.

Nearest to Amia of all the Ruathym Jarldoms, Fortress Wiltun stands on a solitary cliff high above the gray beaches of the Sea of Swords. The banner of Fortress Wiltun is the Raven, which hangs from the walls of all Wiltun-protected lands.

Fort Wiltun is easily reached by sailing ship and serves as a major nexus for many other destinations throughout the Sea of Swords and the Trackless Sea. As such, many adventurers have the opportunity to earn some coin and some prestige by working in Wiltun or abroad in Wiltun's interests, as well as the opportunity to spend it in several storefronts. So long as they don't mind paying the local taxes.

Captain Guston's northbound ship sails passengers to an island known as the Kingdom of Barak Runedar, where they'll be welcomed by the industrious dwarves of the frozen wilds. The kingdom consists of the dwarven Citadel and the Blue Bear tribe of northmen in Setersborg.

Whereas the dwarven Citadel and Setersborg offer warm hearths, stout ale, and camaraderie, the rest of Barak Runedar is a place of wild and unpredictable danger. Big game hunting is a major draw to the frozen valleys and the tundra where hungry, territorial northern beasts such as the violent Great Northern Bear, the elusive Northern Sabertooth Tigers, the indomitable Mega-Bison and the bloodthirsty Northern Dodo roam and hunt. Orcs, violent barbarians, frost giants, howling yeti, grim fey, snow beasts, and an underkingdom full of fire giants hound hunters and adventurers the whole of the way. Old paths through the snowy forests and up to Grumdek Murr's peak are treacherous to any foreign traveler, and even locals avoid the northwest side of the mountains, a frozen wasteland beaten hard by the icy winds from the Trackless Sea.

Setersborg is nestled just north of the Citadel port through a brief jaunt across snowy hills laden with bears and dodos. Setersborg is a small, warm village housing a tribe of northmen, where travelers and adventurers can seek shelter and a drink to warm them. Staunch allies of the dwarves, they enjoy the protection of the dwarven Kingdom of Barak Runedar.

A traveler's first destination in the Jarldom of Ostland is the southernmost port of Osthavn, one of many shipping destinations in the Sea of Swords. The town is small and humble, with little to offer besides good company, directions to other Ostlander locales, and a side of wariness against spellcasters and druids. While the Jarldom of Ostland neither bars access nor persecutes either, some of the older generation remember a different, more dangerous time. They are a welcoming folk, though, provided you mean no harm.

Ostdur is the seat of the Jarl of Ostland, located in the mountainous hills northwest of Osthavn. The Jarl is the foremost authority in all of Ostland, and has been known to call upon citizens and guests alike to attend his court in Ostdur. His word is law, and the Everwatch Knights are sworn to his service.

Havskar is located far to the north of Osthavn. It is a small village of fishermen and farmers, with the occasional kobold spotted coming to and fro. The people are more laid back and friendly in Havskar, wholly welcoming to anyone who comes to visit - and to spend their coin.

Howness is a port city on the northern end of the island of Forrstakkr. It is home to followers of Helm and headed by a Council of Elders. The people of Howness are insular and abrasive with unknown travelers, but it is said they may warn up to you over time if you help them out.
Thordstein is a small village located along the southwest coast. It is home to a small library, but mostly serves as housing for the small, dedicated staff.
Thykkvi is a small monastery located on the southeast coast of Forrstakkr. It is home to a humble order of monks who dedicate their efforts to the well-being of the people of Forrstakkr.

Djedet is a Mulhorandi village in Khem, located due south from Nes'ek. Once the center of a great war involving Anubis, Djedet has a rich cultural history and stands as a bastion of the Mulhorandi faith despite its small size. It is said they have a friendly relationship with some of the political powers on the isle of Amia.

Hangman's Cove is a seedy town nestled on an island called Demonreach. Once said to be a living, moving island, Demonreach has since gone still and now rests comfortably near the northwestern edge of the Korinn Archipelago in the Sea of Swords. The wilds outside of Hangman's Cove are filled with deadly beasts and strange creatures. Travelers are on their own if they venture past the walls.

Home to vicious pirates and intrepid buccaneers, Hangman's Cove is most known for the many "amenities" provided, especially within The Mermaid's Tail, a tawdry tavern and brothel.

Chillwyck is a bastion of the Aurilite faith. Citizens and travelers alike are forbidden from using heat-producing flames in any way while within this territory. Their laws are harsh and strict, but overall viewed as reasonable, especially given the ferocity of their faith.

Belenoth is nestled in the snowy mountains of the Frozenfar. Once known as Barak Tungstuk, it is now a haven for misfits and outcasts, a center of knowledge and learning for people of all walks of life.

The dwarven port and citadel are nestled on the southeastern side of Barak Runedar's two mountains, Khazat Murr and the larger Grumdek Murr. The Citadel touts a healthy trade in the riches of the earth, chiefly gemstones and mineral ores, as well as expert stonework architecture shaped by skilled dwarven crafters who live and work under the watchful and ever present gaze of the dwarven pantheon, the Morndinsamman. The dwarves are known for their penchant for ale and spirits as they are for their steadfastness and love of a good fight; at the right hour of the day, both can be found in the renowned citadal brewery.


The authorities of Barak Runedar insist upon the following disclaimer: "Follow the laws of the Barak Runedar; respect our heritage and gods. Ignorance of the law excuses it not. Do these and enjoy all that Barak Runedar has to offer. The royal family of Barak Runedar thanks you and greets you warmly to our halls."

Zanshibon is located in the 363rd Layer of the Abyss and is ruled by the demon Paush. All manner of beings are allowed to enter Zanshibon, but they must abide by the Lord's rules, which essentially mean that whatever he says goes.

Adventurers often travel to this layer of the Abyss to cut through the hordes of demons in the abyssal wastes. Paush allows this, as it serves his purposes well enough and brings him both amusement and prosperity in the way of trade within the city bazaar.

Insulting Paush in any way is highly discouraged for anyone who is fond of their mortal soul.

Greengarden stands where once the Holy City of Kohlingen stood. The land has seen many trials throughout the years. Beset by dragons at least once a decade, the Holy City finally fell in fire and shadow for all its efforts to stand against the wicked. Now, it has been rebuilt anew, a Duchy within the larger Kingdom of Kohlingen. Known most for its extensive farming background, it also has a strong Tempuran presence. Much of the duchy remains wild and green, however, a testament to its name.
